A frog is a small tailless amphibian that typically has a green or brown body and can change its skin color for camouflage Frogs have protruding eyes webbed toes and long hind legs for jumping They live on all continents except Antarctica and spend their lives near water such as ponds lakes and marshes where they eat insects worms and other small animals Frogs are amphibians meaning they can live both on land and in water They are cold-blooded meaning their body temperature changes with the temperature of their surroundings Most frogs lay their eggs in water where the tadpoles hatch and then grow into adults Frogs are an important part of the ecosystem because they eat insects which helps to control the insect population They are also a food source for many animals such as snakes birds and mammals